#+TITLE: Slam Bidding

* Slam Bidding

Meta agreements and some slam finding conventions

** General Strategy

- when one knows that we lack the assets for slam (regardless if controls are good), or controls are known to be missing
  then sign off - a basic principle!
- slam trys opposite a very limited hand are serious, that is not highly speculative, so when slam is possible opposite
  a perfect minimum range hand
- serious slam trys opposite very limited hands imply that we have the assets for slam and that only controls matter
- very limited hands should therefore show controls below the trump suit and not worry about extra values
- somewhat limited hands (e.g. 11--15) can e.g. bypass 4M with some extras and a missing control
- somewhat limited hands (e.g. 11--15?) may skip control showing if minimum and bad fitting
- neither cue bids nor last train show better hands than the other, flexibility is needed to get the most useful
  information
- skipping cue bids up the line to use last train would usually imply someone has a wide range and so it's a more
  quantitative ask
- after both partners cue bid, should we last train at all? perhaps only if both are ambiguous wide ranging? how wide?
- splinters usually imply a hand that won't go to slam without a fitting hand from partner - consider if bidding on
  regardless that maybe it's best to find a way to control bid without revealing your shape, however, maybe the fitting
  hand was required for the grand slam and not the small slam
- statistically do not expect a splinter to line up well against a strong 20+ balanced hand - it is likely they have
  some wasted values, though you maybe ok opposite a shapely hand (e.g. Acol 2) that is more based on tricks
- the responder to a splinter can go on with enough extras despite not fitting (e.g. ~13+ opening values outside splinter suit)
- the cue bidding style means we do not show shortage in partner's suit, even though with a big trump fit it can make sense
- supporting partner's suit after agreeing a different trump suit is natural double fit finding if we have only shown 2 suits
- with only the trump suit shown, the first slam try control bid is honour showing
- 3N is natural, not serious in only a few specific situations, e.g. 1M--2N--3C--3N

** What is 4N?

Natural quantitative, to play, ace asking, key card asking, takeout or other?


*** Minor Agreed 4N

- both minors supported, or 5--5+ opposite known balanced hand - [Double Fit RKB](#Double Fit RKB)
- jump 4N - quantitative
- non-jump 4N with limited hand - natural, to play
- after Redwood - natural, to play (not King ask etc.)

*** Major Agreed/Implied 4N

- two suits naturally supported, at least one major, or 5--5+ opposite known balanced hand - [Double Fit RKB](#Double Fit RKB)
- raised or set suit - [RKB](#RKB 4N)
- long good 6+ suit implied (eg. 3 level jump overcall) - [RKB](#RKB 4N)

*** Others 4N

- Partner *never* bid - Takeout
- 1 minor then over jump 4 level interference - Takeout/Unusual
- jump response to Takeout double without interference - Quantitative
- jump 4N with all suits bid and no fit found - Quantitative
- jump 4N when easy way to force and set suit major available - Quantitative
- 1N opened or overcalled, and no major set, and after non-slam try stayman transfers - Quantitative
- NT bid raised (including "NT" bids by artificial means) - Quantitative
- non-jump 4N with limited hand - natural, to play
- long natural major (1!h/!s) then over jump 4 level interference - [RKB](#RKB 4N)
- long natural minor (2!c/!d) then over jump 4 level interference - Quantitative

** Q-Minorwood

Quantitative Minorwood - bidding the 4 level minor trump suit as RKB with quantitative step. Let's responder give an
opinion on whether they have a worse or better slam going hand, the initial step response simply being a "reject".

Note, similar but higher, is (optional) "Auto RKB" where we pass 4N if minimum, otherwise respond as RKB.

- next step rejects, follow up is RKB
- higher bid auto RKB, accept slam try

i.e with natural bidding:

4C = natural, showing !cs
    4D = reject slam try
        4H = RKB anyway
    4H = 1/4 KC, RKB responses
    4S = 3/0 KC
    4N = 2/5 KC
    5C = 2/5 KC + Queen

4D = natural, !ds
    4H = reject slam try
        4S = RKB anyway
    4S = 1/4 KC, RKB responses
    4N = 3/0 KC
    5C = 2/5 KC
    5D = 2/5 KC + Queen

WHEN is 4m actually Q-Minorwood?

- (a) when is it on versus a flattish limited hand?
- (b) when is it on versus an unbalanced hand?
- just forcing, offering control or natural bidding if neither (a) nor (b) apply

*** 4CD vs Balanced/Defined Hands

Where *all* apply:

- (1) one hand shows a limited (fairly defined) flattish hand. E.g 2N opening/rebid/overcall, 1N opening. Such a hand is
  unlikely to need to describe their own suits
- (2) the partner shows a minor suit slam try at the 4 level (making agreeing and using something like Redwood impractical)
- (3) no chance for the flattish hand to show whether a minor slam try is feasible earlier on in the bidding

Examples:

- 1N--2N--3D--4D. Whilst 2N transfer shows !ds, the focus was on 3N / general game finding until 4D as a slam try was
  made
- 1N--2S--2N--3S--3N--4C. Shows !s singleton then bids onto 4C after 3N attempted sign off
- 1N--2S--2N--4C. Similar, late reveal of a slam try
- 1N--3C--3D--4m. Puppet Stayman then showing 5+ minor
- 1N--2C--2M--3m--3x--4m. Was finding best game until 4m implied slam interest
- 2N--3C--3D--4D. 4 level first time to show !ds, to even suggest !d slam try
- 2N--3C--3S--4D. Same, first time to show !ds. 4H only way to slam try !ss
- 1C--2D--3D--3x--4D. Similarly, game focussed opposite flat hand, until rebid 4m
- 1C--2H--3m--3x--4m. Same, only responder stronger balanced.
- 1D--2D--2H--2S--2N--3DHS--3N--4D. When the limited flattish hand could have 1--3 !ds, asking rather than Minorwood better
- 1M--2m--2N--4m. Again flattish opener, responder may want some indication of reject or accept

**** Flattish Q-Minorwood Variants 1 Bid Lower

Note there are some auctions where the bid below the minor suit shows a slam try in the minor suit. Responses are
similar just 1 bid lower:

- 1N--2N--3m--4C. Shows !d slam try with !c singleton, then similar
- 2N--4C. Artificial !d single suiter shown, then straight into the usual responses

*** 4CD vs Unbalanced Hands

Even when both hands are unbalanced, sometimes bidding 4m as RKB instead of 4m+1 (Redwood) makes much more sense due to
who is the auction's captain, who is (more) unlimited, or the general difficulty in setting trumps before being able to
use Redwood.

- game forcing constructive auctions
- Not just best game finding. Not preemptive. Not competitive
- 4m bidder is the captain, potentially unlimited (which is assumed if jump bidding 4m!). If limited and seeking
  cooperation then 4m is more general slam try last train like before Redwood
- either minor AGREED OR self JUMP 4m (re)bids showing good (often self-sufficient) hands


** Constrained Auto RKB

Some situations with limited space we may choose to signoff with bad holdings.

- Sign off: 0/1 KC (maybe judged "bad" 2KC)

Step responses for the rest, skipping sign off bid:

- 2 no Q
- 2 with Q
- 3+ KC
- higher void + 2KC

Until further experimentation decides otherwise, Queen ask and 5N King ask on if space permits. Similar to EKB.


** Flag Bidding

Artificial bids to slam try from a selection of suits. Often when a two suiter has been shown. Sometimes we might bid a
minor at the 4 level naturally as the slam try, but a special bid is needed to slam try in the major at the 4 level.

"Flag bids (sometimes called "flag" or "pointer" bids in advanced cuebidding literature, e.g., in works like Ken
Rexford's Cuebidding at Bridge or certain 2/1 and NT system notes) are artificial bids that "flag" or point to one
specific suit among a known selection (often a two-suiter) as the potential trump suit for a slam try. They are
especially useful at the 4-level or higher when space is tight, you cannot naturally show interest in multiple suits
without bypassing key levels, or you need to distinguish slam interest in a major versus a minor."

When:

- Clear situation where *expected to choose* one of the suits (or rarely sign off in your own suit)
- Have not agreed the suit yet
- Choosing naturally already reaches Game or goes too high in some way

Core Rules, focussed on below game flags or 4N meanings:

- 4CD supporting/choosing a minor IS a FLAG for the minor, the weakest hands may fast arrival bid 5CD
- 4CD supporting/choosing a minor is NEVER a major flag (intuitively)
- Major contracts > Minor contracts...
- Minor + Major -> 4N is Major RKB
- Both Majors -> 4N is !ss highest rank RKB, *5C is artificial* !h RKB IFF no lower flag available
- Both Minors 4N -> "natural", depending on how high either to play or quantitative
- 1 flag free, Major + Minor, major takes priority, maybe Last Train like suggesting slam but not wanting to push 4N major RKB
- 1 flag for both Minors, flags the highest rank suit (e.g. when 4!s is the only flag bid free before 5m)
- 1 flag for both Majors, flags *lowest* rank suit as 4N is highest rank RKB
- 2 flags for both majors (rare below game), lowest bid to low rank, highest bid to high rank
- 2 flag bids otherwise, then natural is natural flag, otherwise low bid to low rank, high bid to high rank

In these situations you would never have a chance to agree both suits naturally and use [Double Fit RKB](#Double Fit RKB),
however the double fit rules make an exception for known balanced hands opposite 5--5+ hands.

Remember in desperate low space auctions consider these options:

- [Lackwood](#Lackwood)
- [5NT Pick a Small Slam](#5NT Pick a Small Slam)

*** Flags Above Game?

Is the flag *forced* to be above 1 game (i.e the 4M game) or is it above both games (at least 5!c bid)?

- 4S if !hs + minor (above 1 game)
- 5C if major + !ds (above 1 game)
- 5D if major + !cs (above 2 games)
- 5m if majors (above 2 games)
- 5M if minors (above 2 games)

The 4N (instead of doing a flag bid) meaning is unchanged, when available.

- majors still priority
- flags below 4N, i.e 4S when e.g. !hs possible contract will flag the major in a last train / quantitative cooperative
  slam try minor with 4N still being RKB for major
- other flags go beyond 4N

**** Responding to above game flags (above 1+ game)

Play [Constrained Auto RKB](#Constrained Auto RKB). Rejects with limited keycards. Less nuance than
[Q-Minorwood](#Q-Minorwood), though might decide in context that 2KC no Queen is worth a downgrade.


*** 6--4 opener example

- 1H--1S--2N--3C--3H ...

Here opener normally has a 6--4 hand, the 3C bid asks and 3H shows !cs (3!d would show !ds). At this point 3S is just NF
natural with !ss and disinterest in both of opener's suits.

When responder has a slam going hand we must distinguish just playing game in openers suits (!hs or !cs) and slam trying
in both of them, setting trumps.

- 4m (4!c in this case) flags, does a slam try in, opener's !c suit
- 4om (4!d here) flags the !h suit for a slam try
- 4M is just to play as would 5C
- note, if responder had very good slam try !s suit they should have bid 3S over 2N or bid a 4m auto-splinter

*** 6--5 responder example

But what if the decision is pushed higher?

- 1N--2N--3C--3S--3N--4H

After the !d transfer responder shows a !s shortage and then 6--5 shape with 5!hs (very rare).

- 4S flags the !h slam try, major priority
- 4N !h RKB, we only only had 1 flag free
- 5C is !d flag, [Constrained Auto RKB](#Constrained Auto RKB)

Awkward rare auction where not clear if opener should bid on if they find a !h fit or just pass.

*** 2C opener 6--5 example

- 2C--2D--3S

- 4C as [Q-Minorwood](#Q-Minorwood) slam try
- 4D as flag slam try for the major, !ss in this case
- 4H probably confusing, should be own very good suit

*** 2C responder 5--5 example

- 2C--2N--3C--3S

A 5--5+ !d + !s hand.

- 3N misfit
- 4C excellent 7+ suit, with 4H then a flag for !cs
- 4D as [Q-Minorwood](#Q-Minorwood) !d slam try
- 4H as flag for !s slam try
- 4S to play

*** Michaels example

- (1H)--2H--2N--3S

Showing !ss + !ds with extras.

- 4C is now flag for !ss
- 4D as [Q-Minorwood](#Q-Minorwood) slam try
- 4H control bid, suggests !c weakness, major implicit agreed

*** Competitive Examples

See these documented elsewhere...

- (1H)--2H--(3H)--4N only minor ask with slam interest
- (2S)--3S--4N only minor ask slam interest
- (3C)--4C majors
- (3C)--4D !ds + major, 5d play
- (2S)--4C--4S club slam try, 5C signoff, [Constrained Auto RKB](#Constrained Auto RKB)
- (2S)--4D--4S heart slam try, 5H signoff, [Constrained Auto RKB](#Constrained Auto RKB)
- (2S)--4D--5C !d slam try, 5D signoff, [Constrained Auto RKB](#Constrained Auto RKB)
- (2H)--3H--(4H) now 4N probably still strong minor ask
- (4H)--5H too high to anything but guess if have 1.5 tricks then bid slam
- (4S)--4N no flags


