"""
| Factor | Favours Italian/Mixed Cues | Favours Ace-Showing Cues |
|---|---|---|
| **Hand shape** | Both hands balanced or semi-balanced (5-3-3-2, 4-4-3-2, 5-4-2-2) | At least one hand shapely (singletons, voids, 6-4, 5-5) |
| **Shape already shown?** | No prior splinter or shortness-showing bid | Splinter or shape-showing bid already made |
| **What matters most** | Binary "are we off two cashers?" check | Accurate trick-counting opposite known shape |
| **Bidding space** | Tight (high-level agreement, e.g. 4M after splinter) | Plentiful (low agreement, e.g. 3♣ or 3♦) |
| **Trump suit level** | High (4-level agreement) | Low (3-level agreement) |
| **Partnership skill** | Strong expert pair, comfortable with inference and captaincy | Improver/intermediate, or new partnership |
| **Failure mode you fear most** | Missing a slam because you couldn't locate a useful king | Bidding slam off two cashing tricks due to ambiguous cue |
| **Auction type** | NT-based slam tries, balanced strong-club auctions | Major-suit auctions with shapely opener or responder |
| **Honour distribution** | Honours scattered across several suits | Honours concentrated, shape carries the value |
| **Tolerance for ambiguity** | High — willing to trade specificity for speed | Low — wants explicit, unambiguous content |

A useful way to read the table: if most of your row-answers fall in the left column on a given hand-type, Italian cues earn their keep; if most fall right, ace-showing is doing real work. Most partnerships face a *mix* of these situations across a session, which is why expert pairs increasingly play hybrid agreements — for instance, ace-showing in partner's known long suit (where shape ambiguity is most damaging) but mixed cues in unbid suits (where space efficiency matters most).
"""

